@flexiarg math-strategy/non-circularity-check
@title Non-Circularity Check
@sigils [🔄/非]
@keywords nontrivial, circular, independence, construction, target, bootstrap, witness
@audience mathematicians, proof-writers
@tone heuristic
@factor Persistence (viriya)

! conclusion:
  When you construct an object to witness an existence claim, verify that the
  construction does not secretly depend on the thing you are trying to prove exists.

  + context: You are proving "there exists X with property P" by exhibiting a
    concrete X. The construction uses ingredients (parameters, formulas, prior
    results) that might implicitly assume P already holds.

  + IF:
      Your construction involves the same mathematical objects that appear in the
      target property (e.g., building a Markov chain whose stationary distribution
      involves certain polynomials, using transition rates that might depend on
      those same polynomials).

  + HOWEVER:
      Not all apparent circularity is real. A construction may use the same
      *notation* as the target without logical dependence — the transition rates
      may be defined purely from combinatorial data, even though the stationary
      distribution involves special functions. The check must be precise about
      what "depends on" means.

  + THEN:
      (a) List every ingredient of the construction (parameters, rates, rules).
      (b) For each ingredient, trace its definition: does it reference the
          target property or the objects whose existence you claim?
      (c) If yes: either restructure the construction to remove the dependence,
          or prove that the dependence is only apparent (e.g., the formula
          simplifies to something independent).
      (d) State the non-circularity explicitly in the proof ("note that the
          transition rates depend only on x, t, and the current configuration,
          not on values of F*_μ").

  + BECAUSE:
      Circularity in existence proofs is subtle and common. The most dangerous
      form is a construction that "works" only because it smuggles the
      conclusion into the premises. Reviewers trained in constructive mathematics
      will spot this; the rest will be misled. An explicit non-circularity
      statement inoculates the proof.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[List all ingredients of the construction.]
    next[Trace each ingredient to its definition.]
    next[Flag any that reference the target property.]
    next[Resolve or state the independence explicitly.]
